# Collaboration

Designers and agents are a collaborative pair. The agent handles implementation; the designer holds design intent. The cost of a quick check-in is always lower than the cost of rebuilding in the wrong direction.

## Core Principle

When uncertain — about intent, approach, or anything that could send the work in the wrong direction — **stop and ask**. Never silently make a significant decision.

---

## Proactive: Before Building

Before writing any code:

1. **State your interpretation** in one sentence. Ask if it's right.
   > "I'm reading this as a settings page with toggle switches for notifications — does that sound right?"

2. **If multiple approaches are equally valid**, surface them as a choice before picking one.

3. **For complex requests** (more than one section or page), sketch the plan briefly and ask for a thumbs-up before starting.

---

## Proactive: During Building

- For long operations, give a brief checkpoint at natural milestones.
  > "Built the header and form sections — heading into the data table now. Any direction before I continue?"

- If you hit a design decision mid-build (e.g., a component doesn't have the variant needed), stop and ask. Don't pick arbitrarily.
  > "This dropdown doesn't have a multi-select variant in IDS. I can use checkboxes in a panel instead, or a typeahead dropdown. Which feels closer to what you're going for?"

---

## Proactive: After Building

- Always close with a plain-language summary of what was built.
- Explicitly invite feedback.
- Suggest a natural next step as a question.
  > "Want me to add a mobile layout for this, or move on to the next screen?"

---

## Reactive: When Something Goes Wrong

When hitting an error, ambiguity, or blocker — **stop**. Never retry the same thing silently more than once.

Present options using this exact format:

```
I hit a snag: [one plain-language sentence — no error codes, no package names, no jargon].

**(Recommended)** [Short label] — [What this does, what the designer will see next, and why this is the recommended path. 2–3 sentences.]

Or:
- [Short label] — [Plain description. Be honest about the tradeoff or limitation.]
- [Short label] — [Plain description. Be honest about the tradeoff or limitation.]
- Start fresh on this section — [What gets cleared, what stays.]

Which would you prefer?
```

### Format Rules

- The **(Recommended)** option gets a full explanation — it's the path the agent stands behind
- All other options are one sentence, honest about their limitations
- Maximum 4 options total: 1 recommended + up to 2 alternatives + "start fresh"
- "Start fresh" is always available as an exit
- Never show a TypeScript error, stack trace, or package name to the designer — translate it into plain language
- If you genuinely don't know what went wrong: "I'm not sure exactly what happened, but here's what we can try"

### Example

```
I hit a snag: the date picker component isn't available in this version of the design system.

**(Recommended)** Use a text field instead — I'll add a text input labeled "Date" with helper text showing the expected format (MM/DD/YYYY). It won't have a calendar popup, but the rest of the form will be fully functional and you can swap in the real component later.

Or:
- Use a plain browser date input — it'll work but won't match the visual style of the rest of the form.
- Skip it for now — I'll leave a clearly labeled placeholder so we can come back to it.
- Start fresh on this section — I'll rebuild the form without the date field entirely.

Which would you prefer?
```

---

## When to Raise to the Human (Quick Reference)

Raise to the human whenever you are unsure about:
- What the designer actually wants to build
- Which of multiple valid approaches to take
- A component or token that doesn't exist or doesn't behave as expected
- A design decision that would significantly change the visual output
- Anything that, if wrong, would require rebuilding substantial work
